        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our previous SMA observations reveal a percentage polarization of 4.6% for OH 231-8+4.2 and a peak Stokes I intensity of 0.78 Jy/beam at 345 GHz (2.5"x2"). To obtain a 0.1% calibration accuracy this translates into 40 microJy/beam (decreasing when going off-peak) in ALMA. This sensitivity, reachable within the 3 hours observing period allowed for polarization studies, is sufficient to detect polarization close to the central part as well as the faint (extended) features.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use 4 spectral windows, each of width 1875 MHz, and with center rest frequencies of 336.5, 338.5, 348.5, &amp; 350.5 GHz, with the lowest velocity resolution available, since we are only interested in continuum measurements.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request a resolution of 0.5" to resolve the small scale structures in both of our objects since we need to probe the magnetic field configuration as close to the central star as possible in order to probe the launching mechanism. In the case of OH 231.8+4.2, at this resolution, most of the bright continuum emission (spread over ~7 arcsec) fits within the 1/3 beam required for polarization. We aim at a significant enhancement in resolution from previous SMA polarization observations at 2" resolution. We also aim to detect a suspected toroidal configuration. The combination of all the data previously obtained at larger scale (SMA and masers) will therefore allow us to "reconstruct" the magnetic field topology. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
