        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We expect the Red Rectangle to show a percentage polarization below the level found for OH 231.8+4.2 due to its carbon-rich nature. ALMA observations of the continuum emission (Bujarrabal et al.2013) at approximately the same resolution (0.48"x0.44") as we are requesting, indicate that the peak intensity is 364 mJy/beam. Assuming 0.1% calibration accuracy, this imposes a sensitivity requirement of 364 microJy/beam. As in the case of our other source (OH231.8+4.2), this sensitivity is reachable within the 3 hours observing period allowed for polarization studies, and will allow us to adequately probe the polarization in the internal parts of the object. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use 4 spectral windows, each of width 1875 MHz, and with center rest frequencies of 336.5, 338.5, 348.5, &amp; 350.5 GHz, with the lowest velocity resolution available, since we are only interested in continuum measurements.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The Red Rectangle has already been observed with ALMA at approximately the same resolution as in our study to trace its outflows in CO emission. Our matching observations will therefore allow us to trace the magnetic field configuration in the outflow region, and thus test models for the launching and collimation of the outflows by magnetic fields. Here again, the size of the continuum, 4"x2", fits within the 1/3 beam required for polarization.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
